data.title: A U.S.-China Trade War With Students and Tourists as Potential Pawns
data.description: With travel warnings and revoked visas, the two superpowers locked in a bruising trade war may make students and tourists their bargaining chips.

data.title: Keith Siegel, a Former Hostage, Recounts Captivity in Gaza
data.description: Keith Siegel, who spent 484 days as a hostage, described the physical and psychological distress he endured, in an interview with The New York Times.

data.title: UK Supreme Court Says Trans Women Are Not Legally Women Under Equality Act
data.description: Britain’s Supreme Court ruled that the word “woman” refers to biological sex under the country’s anti-discrimination law, in a blow to trans rights activists.

data.title: Its Journalism Challenged Autocrats. Trump Wants to Silence It.
data.description: Journalists at Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty who have been imprisoned for their work are dismayed by the effort to close the outlet.

data.title: Italy’s Meloni Heads to Washington to Meet Trump. Will It Pay Off for Europe?
data.description: The stakes are high as Giorgia Meloni, a conservative who shares some of Mr. Trump’s nationalist ideology, meets with him on Thursday as his trade war has frayed nerves worldwide.

data.title: Israel Threatens Further Escalation in Gaza War
data.description: The United Nations warned that the humanitarian situation in Gaza was likely at its worst since the conflict began and that the population was again on the brink of famine.

data.title: R.S.F. in Sudan Declare Parallel Government Amid Assault on Zamzam Camp
data.description: The United Nations said that at least 300 people were killed when the armed group, the Rapid Support Forces, stormed a camp in Darfur.

data.title: Bukele Has Power to Return Deportee in El Salvador to U.S., Experts Say
data.description: Experts say President Nayib Bukele has the power but not the interest to return a man deported from Maryland to El Salvador in error.

data.title: Latvia Exits Land Mine Convention Amid Fears of Russian Aggression
data.description: The government, along with two other Baltic nations and Poland, agreed last month to quit the 1997 accord that prohibits from using anti-personnel mines. Russia’s invasion of Ukraine was cited as a key reason.

data.title: Peru’s Former First Lady Flees as She and Ex-President Are Sentenced to Prison
data.description: Former President Ollanta Humala and his wife, Nadine Heredia, were sentenced on Tuesday to 15 years in prison for money laundering. Brazil granted her diplomatic asylum, officials said.

data.title: European Spa Company Therme Misrepresented Itself in an Effort to Expand Into Canada
data.description: A Times investigation shows Therme, a European firm, exaggerated its track record in securing a deal with Ontario, and government auditors found that the process had been unfair and opaque.

data.title: Palliative Care Doctor Is Charged With Serial Murder of 15 Patients in Germany
data.description: The Berlin doctor, who was not named because of privacy laws, is also accused of setting fire to some of the patients’ homes to hide evidence.

data.title: Pope Francis Thanks Doctors and Nurses for His Recovery
data.description: Although the pontiff has begun meeting with more people, he remains frail and will not lead important Easter events, the Vatican announced.

data.title: Russia Jails 4 Journalists for Working With Navalny’s Organization
data.description: The case highlighted the perils of independent journalism amid an intensified Kremlin crackdown on freedom of expression.

data.title: American Pastor Kidnapped in South Africa Is Rescued After Shootout
data.description: Three suspects were killed as the police moved in on a safe house where the pastor from Tennessee was being held.

data.title: Trump Aides Close State Dept. Office on Foreign Disinformation
data.description: Secretary of State Marco Rubio put about 40 employees on leave who had tracked disinformation by China, Russia, Iran and terrorist groups.

data.title: 2 Judges Order Federal Agencies to Unfreeze Climate Money
data.description: The rulings are setbacks to Trump’s efforts to halt climate and environmental funding approved under the Biden administration.

data.title: Europeans Show Less Stock Market Panic as Tariffs Cause Turmoil
data.description: Europeans tend to keep more of their money in cash, gaining some protection from the recent market volatility. But President Trump’s tariffs will have an effect, experts said.

data.title: Canada Reschedules Political Debate That Conflicted With a Hockey Game
data.description: A big game, but still.

data.title: The Grand Egyptian Museum Is Finally Open. (Well, Mostly.)
data.description: The Grand Egyptian Museum, outside Cairo, has been delayed by revolutions, wars, financial crises and a pandemic. At long last, here’s a look inside.

data.title: Mexico’s Reliance on U.S. Natural Gas Could Be Its Achilles’ Heel
data.description: Mexico’s imports of U.S. natural gas are surging, kindling fears that the Trump administration could weaponize this trade.

data.title: In Toronto, the Fight to Preserve Ontario Place Turns Into a Farewell
data.description: Generations of visitors have loved the little island complex called Ontario Place in downtown Toronto. It’s about to change forever.

data.title: Wednesday Briefing: A Trump-Harvard Showdown
data.description: Plus, a fight over Van Gogh’s roots.

data.title: Trump Has Mixed Emotions Toward Japan
data.description: The president at turns praises and criticizes Japan, a U.S. ally that decades ago stirred his anger over the unequal balance of trade and his penchant for tariffs.

data.title: Wednesday Briefing: A Trump-Harvard Showdown
data.description: Plus, the fight over Van Gogh’s roots.

data.title: 19 Big Cats Rescued in Spain as Police Raid Animal Smuggling Ring
data.description: With a demand for exotic felines on the rise, often driven by social media, endangered and protected populations are under even more threat.

data.title: Sperm Donors Fathered More Than 25 Children Each, Netherlands Data Reveals
data.description: The numbers raise concerns about the risk of genetic anomalies as those children eventually seek partners and give birth.

data.title: The First Ever Sighting of a Colossal Squid
data.description: An expedition spotted a baby of the species in the South Sandwich Islands. This cephalopod can grow to more than 20 feet and has proved elusive in its deep-sea environs.

data.title: How Trump Might Unwittingly Cut Emissions From Online Shopping
data.description: Fast fashion retailers rely heavily on shipping by air. The president’s tariffs could change that.

data.title: Autopsies of Slain Gaza Medics Show Some Were Shot in the Head
data.description: The New York Times obtained autopsy reports for 14 of the 15 people killed in a March 23 attack on an ambulance and fire truck.

data.title: The ‘Great Moose Migration’ Livestream Captivates Sweden
data.description: Moose fans are following the weekslong moose migration, which airs live on the national broadcaster. “This is reality TV at its finest,” a moderator of a zealous Facebook group said.

data.title: American Airlines Will Offer Free Wi-Fi on Most Flights Next Year
data.description: Starting in January, members of the airline’s AAdvantage loyalty program will have free access to wireless internet on 90 percent of its fleet, the company said.

data.title: Jordan Says It Foiled a Plot Against the Kingdom
data.description: The country’s main intelligence branch said the plans, apparently years in the making, involved rockets, weapons manufacturing and drones.

data.title: Palm Sunday Attack Leaves Sumy Residents Doubtful of a Ukraine-Russia Cease-Fire
data.description: People in the Ukrainian city struck on Palm Sunday have little hope of a cease-fire.

data.title: France Says It Will Expel 12 Algerian Officials
data.description: The move followed expulsions of French officials by Algeria after an Algerian official was accused of kidnapping an influencer who had been granted political asylum in France.

data.title: Santa Lives in Rovaniemi, Finland. Some of His Neighbors Are Not Thrilled.
data.description: A tourist season that stretches from October to March has been anything but jolly for some residents of the “Official Hometown of Santa Claus.”

data.title: Attackers Target Prisons in France, Burning Vehicles and Firing Shots
data.description: The office of France’s counterterrorism prosecutor said it would begin an investigation into the violence. The justice minister blamed drug traffickers.

data.title: Sandstorm Turns Iraq’s Skies Orange and Sends Thousands to Hospitals
data.description: Climate experts say such storms are becoming more frequent and severe in the country. This was its worst of the year so far.

data.title: Head of Kuwait Specialty Field Hospital in Gaza Says Israeli Strike Killed a Guard
data.description: Israel’s military did not immediately comment on the report, which came two days after it attacked the Ahli Arab Hospital in Gaza City.

data.title: Van Gogh’s Last Painting Poses a Problem for an Idyllic French Village
data.description: It was recently determined that the artist painted his final work, “Tree Roots,” in Auvers-sur-Oise. The roots still exist, igniting a fight over their preservation.

data.title: Inside Trump’s Rushed Effort to Deport 238 Migrants
data.description: The Trump administration sent them to a prison in El Salvador under a wartime act, calling them members of a Venezuelan gang. But a New York Times investigation found little evidence of criminal backgrounds or links to the gang.

data.title: In Argentina, a Boom in Antarctic Cruises Is Straining the ‘End of the World’
data.description: Crowds of tourists bound for Antarctica have brought prosperity to Argentina’s southernmost city, but the boom is also squeezing locals and stressing the environment.

data.title: Tuesday Briefing: El Salvador Will Not Return Deportee
data.description: Plus, remembering Mario Vargas Llosa.

data.title: Airport Warned Repeatedly on Bird Strikes Before Fatal Jeju Air Plane Crash
data.description: Operators of the airport where Jeju Air Flight 2216 crashed in December, killing 179, failed to meet both international and South Korean guidelines intended to prevent such strikes.

data.title: A Crisis at a British Steel Mill Has Cast a Shadow Over U.K.-China Relations
data.description: Britain was edging closer to China, but a dispute at a Chinese-owned steel company in the U.K. may prompt a rethink.

data.title: Trump’s Dilemma: A Trade War That Threatens Every Other Negotiation With China
data.description: President Trump is staking everything on winning by imposing tariffs on China. But the fight threatens to choke off negotiations about other issues like Taiwan, fentanyl, TikTok and more.

data.title: Trump Administration Memo Proposes Cutting State Department Funding by Nearly Half
data.description: The draft plan is part of a process involving the agency and the White House. It would eliminate almost all funding for international organizations that include the United Nations and NATO.

data.title: China’s Halt of Critical Minerals Poses Risk for U.S. Military Programs
data.description: The Pentagon and defense contractors are heavily reliant on magnets and rare earth minerals mined or processed in China, which has suspended exports of the materials in an escalating trade war.

data.title: Tuesday Briefing: El Salvador Won’t Return Deportee
data.description: Plus, remembering Mario Vargas Llosa.

data.title: Pope Places Antoni Gaudí, ‘God’s Architect,’ on Path to Sainthood
data.description: Pope Francis on Monday signed a decree that recognized the 20th-century visionary’s “heroic virtues” and put him on the path to possible sainthood.

data.title: Hungary Changes Constitution to Mandate Two Genders
data.description: The governing Fidesz party passed a constitutional amendment stating that all Hungarians are either male or female, and another protecting the “moral development” of children.

data.title: Mehul Choksi, Fugitive Jeweler Wanted by India, Is Arrested in Belgium
data.description: The fugitive, Mehul Choksi, is wanted in connection with a major financial scandal at a publicly owned Indian bank. The police in Antwerp, Belgium, arrested him over the weekend.

data.title: Pete Marocco, Who Helped Gut Foreign Aid for Trump, Leaves State Department
data.description: Pete Marocco oversaw the cutting of thousands of contracts at U.S.A.I.D. and the firing of most of its roughly 10,000 workers. Aid agency employees have accused him of mismanagement.

data.title: Trump Calls Russia’s Strike on Sumy a ‘Mistake’
data.description: At least 35 people were killed in the attack on Sumy, which came as Ukraine’s leader urged President Trump to come witness the realities of war firsthand.

data.title: When Elected Leaders Pursue Risky Policies, What Can Stop Them?
data.description: President Trump issued a partial, temporary reprieve on tariffs that had sent the stock market tumbling. He did so only after U.S. government bonds showed signs of distress.

data.title: Military Leader Wins Presidential Election in Gabon
data.description: Brice Oligui Nguema had promised to relinquish power after he led a coup in 2023. He now is set to lead the oil-rich country for the next seven years.

data.title: With Trump’s Tariffs, Europe Fears a Flood of Cheap Goods From China
data.description: President Trump’s tariffs on China could lead to a hazardous scenario for European countries: the dumping of artificially cheap products that could undermine local industries.

data.title: Why a Ukrainian Lawmaker Is Pushing to Legalize Pornography
data.description: Ukraine makes tax revenue off the creators of pornographic content, but also threatens them with prosecution. A draft law aims to fix what many say is an unfair contradiction.

data.title: A Small City That Lost Big in the Dominican Nightclub Tragedy
data.description: Haina, a city just outside the Dominican capital, lost 25 people in the Jet Set disaster, including community leaders and cultural icons.
